HEADWORD: Rancheria
<hw>Ran`che*ri"a</hw> <pr>(r⟦adot⟧n`ch⟦asl⟧"r⟦emac⟧"⟦adot⟧)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Sp. <ets>rancheria</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
dwelling place of a ranchero.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A small settlement or collection of ranchos, or rude
huts, esp. for Indians.</def> <mark>[Sp. Amer. & Southwestern U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Formerly, in the Philippines, a political division
of the pagan tribes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Ranchero</ent>⟦br⟧
